04878nam a22008415i 9780231544375DE-B159720200826040535.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200826t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)984687848  a97802315443757 a10.7312/rend175262doi  a(DE-B1597)480305  a(OCoLC)968246473  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHM851b.R45713 2017 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a303.48/332231 aRendueles, César, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSociophobia :bPolitical Change in the Digital Utopia /cCésar Rendueles. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aInsurrections: Critical Studies in Religion, Politics, and Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword: Culture Industry 2.0, or the End of Digital Utopias in the Era of Participation Culture -- tGround Zero: Sociophobia -- t1. Digital Utopia -- t2. After Capitalism -- tCoda 1989 -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe great ideological cliché of our time, César Rendueles argues in Sociophobia, is the idea that communication technologies can support positive social dynamics and improve economic and political conditions. We would like to believe that the Internet has given us the tools to overcome modernity's practical dilemmas and bring us into closer relation, but recent events show how technology has in fact driven us farther apart.Named one of the ten best books of the year by Babelia El País, Sociophobia looks at the root causes of neoliberal utopia's modern collapse. It begins by questioning the cyber-fetishist dogma that lulls us into thinking our passive relationship with technology plays a positive role in resolving longstanding differences. Rendueles claims that the World Wide Web has produced a diminished rather than augmented social reality. In other words, it has lowered our expectations with respect to political interventions and personal relations. In an effort to correct this trend, Rendueles embarks on an ambitious reassessment of our antagonistic political traditions to prove that post-capitalism is not only a feasible, intimate, and friendly system to strive for but also essential for moving past consumerism and political malaise.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aInformation technologyxSocial aspects. 0aInternetxPolitical aspects. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aCleary, Heather1 aSimanowski, Roberto08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2016-2018z978311066255908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2017z978311065472108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017z978311054330808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2017z9783110548228oZDB-23-DPH40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/rend1752640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231544375423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231544375.jpg  a978-3-11-054330-8  CUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017b2017  a978-3-11-062526-4  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017b2017  a978-3-11-065472-1  CUP eBook Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-066255-9  CUP eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  